"Li Y., Liang F., Bux H., Yang W., Caro J.","Zeolitic imidazolate framework ZIF-7 based molecular sieve membrane for hydrogen separation",2010,"Journal of Membrane Science","354","1-2",,"48","54",,,10.1016/j.memsci.2010.02.074,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77950367754&partnerID=40&md5=4de06f81466669fd15cc745f253ba967","Institute of Physical Chemistry and Electrochemistry, Laboratory for Nano, Quantum Engineering (LNQE) in Cooperation with the Center for Solid State Research and New Materials, Hannover, 30167, Germany; State Key Laboratory of Catalysis, Dalian Institute of Chemical Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Dalian, 116023, China","Li, Y., Institute of Physical Chemistry and Electrochemistry, Laboratory for Nano, Quantum Engineering (LNQE) in Cooperation with the Center for Solid State Research and New Materials, Hannover, 30167, Germany, State Key Laboratory of Catalysis, Dalian Institute of Chemical Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Dalian, 116023, China; Liang, F., Institute of Physical Chemistry and Electrochemistry, Laboratory for Nano, Quantum Engineering (LNQE) in Cooperation with the Center for Solid State Research and New Materials, Hannover, 30167, Germany; Bux, H., Institute of Physical Chemistry and Electrochemistry, Laboratory for Nano, Quantum Engineering (LNQE) in Cooperation with the Center for Solid State Research and New Materials, Hannover, 30167, Germany; Yang, W., State Key Laboratory of Catalysis, Dalian Institute of Chemical Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Dalian, 116023, China; Caro, J., Institute of Physical Chemistry and Electrochemistry, Laboratory for Nano, Quantum Engineering (LNQE) in Cooperation with the Center for Solid State Research and New Materials, Hannover, 30167, Germany","Hydrogen-based energy system could address issues related to global climate change, energy security, and local air pollution. Thermally and hydrothermally stable microporous membranes with intrinsic high H2/CO2 selectivity are highly demanded. A novel zeolitic imidazolate framework (ZIF-7) membrane was tested for its gas separation performance. ZIFs are microporous materials and belong to the new class of metal-organic frameworks (MOFs). ZIF-7 is formed by bridging benzimidazolate anions and zinc cations resulting in a sodalite (SOD) topology with a pore size of about 0.3 nm. The ZIF-7 membrane exhibited promising H2 separation abilities. At 220 °C, the H2 permeance is ∼4.5 × 10-8 mol m-2 s-1 Pa-1 and the mixture separation factors for H2/CO2, H2/N2, and H2/CH4 are 13.6, 18.0, and 14.0, respectively. As a result of molecular sieving mechanism, the ideal selectivities and mixture separation factors are identical. The permeation of H2 through the ZIF-7 membrane is highly activated with an apparent activation energy of 11.9 kJ mol-1. Due to the ultra-hydrophobic properties of ZIF materials, the ZIF-7 membrane also showed excellent hydrothermal stability in the presence of steam. Our results clearly demonstrate that ZIF-7 membranes have an intrinsic high H2/CO2 selectivity and a promising application in hydrogen separation, which is based on its very narrow and well-defined crystal pore structure. © 2010 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Gas separation; Metal-organic frameworks; Molecular sieve membranes; Zeolitic imidazolate frameworks; ZIF-7","Apparent activation energy; Energy security; Energy systems; Gas separations; Global climate changes; Hydrogen separation; Hydrophobic properties; Hydrothermal stabilities; Hydrothermally; Imidazolate; Metal organic framework; Micro porous membranes; Mixture separation; Molecular sieve membranes; Molecular sieving; Separation ability; Activation energy; Air quality; Climate change; Crystal structure; Hydrogen; Materials properties; Microporosity; Microporous materials; Molecular sieves; Sieves; Zinc; Gas permeable membranes; 1,4 butanediol; carbon dioxide; hydrogen; metal organic framework; methane; nitrogen; organic compound; putrescine; unclassified drug; zeolitic imidazolate framework 7; zinc ion; air pollution; analytic method; article; artificial membrane; climate change; controlled study; crystal structure; energy resource; flow kinetics; hydrophobicity; membrane permeability; molecular sieve membrane; priority journal; purification; separation technique; thermostability",,"1,4 butanediol, 110-63-4; carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; hydrogen, 12385-13-6, 1333-74-0; methane, 74-82-8; nitrogen, 7727-37-9; putrescine, 110-60-1, 333-93-7; zinc ion, 23713-49-7",,,,"Dunn, S., Hydrogen futures: toward a sustainable energy system (2002) Int. J. Hydrogen. Energy, 27, pp. 235-264; Rostrup-Nielsen, J.R., Rostrup-Nielsen, T., Large-scale hydrogen production (2002) CATTECH, 6, pp. 150-159; Adhikari, S., Fernando, S., Hydrogen membrane separation techniques (2006) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 45, pp. 875-881; Ockwig, N.W., Nenoff, T.M., Membranes for hydrogen separation (2007) Chem. Rev., 107, pp. 4078-4110; Song, C.S., Fuel processing for low-temperature and high-temperature fuel cells challenges, and opportunities for sustainable development in the 21st century (2002) Catal. Today, 77, pp. 17-49; Dong, J.H., Lin, Y.S., Kanezashi, M., Tang, Z., Microporous inorganic membranes for high temperature hydrogen purification (2008) J. Appl. Phys., 104, p. 121301; Lin, Y.S., Kumakiri, I., Nair, B.N., Alsyouri, H., Microporous inorganic membranes (2002) Sep. Purif. Methods, 31, pp. 229-379; Gao, H.Y., Lin, Y.S., Li, Y.D., Zhang, B.Q., Chemical stability and its improvement of palladium-based metallic membranes (2004) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 43, pp. 6920-6930; Ismail, A.F., David, L.I.B., A review on the latest development of carbon membranes for gas separation (2001) J. Membr. Sci., 193, pp. 1-18; Gu, X.H., Tang, Z., Dong, J.H., On-stream modification of MFI zeolite membranes for enhancing hydrogen separation at high temperature (2008) Micropor. Mesopor. Mater., 111, pp. 441-448; Hong, M., Falconer, J.L., Noble, R.D., M